---
Brawlers are unarmed close-quarters fighters descended from the pugilist tradition — physical fighting disciplines developed by cistern laborers, caravan porters, and bound-service workers at pyramid construction sites during the Solar Court era. These workers developed body knowledge from accumulated necessity: heavy labor and cramped work spaces in high-impact environments created physical adaptations that transferred directly to fighting, and that practical knowledge accumulated across generations without formal instruction. The pugilist disciplines required no equipment, no record, and no institution to survive, which is why they survived every collapse that destroyed more formally documented traditions. The transition to the modern Brawler form happened in the harbor district fighting pits of Kowloon and Mafdet, where the pugilist tradition encountered competitive pressure from opponents who were specifically trying to win. Pit environments drove systematic refinement: techniques that survived adversarial testing against fully resistant opponents are the only ones still taught. The Brawler tradition maintains a strong anti-theoretical stance — not from incuriosity but because pit experience produces consistent evidence that theories about effective fighting fail to predict what works against specific opponents using specific improvisations under specific conditions. Instruction is demonstration-based: the practitioner understands why a technique works by experiencing that it works. Brawlers are the parent tradition feeding the Martial Artist adept synthesis when combined with Monk training.

