---
Midgaard's registry does not maintain a specific Brawler classification; unarmed fighters without institutional affiliation fall under "unlicensed physical practice," applied inconsistently by the Civic Guard.
Brawlers operating as caravan escort file under the same labor contractor registry as armed escorts; pit fighters technically require a performance license from a different office than the one classifying physical practice.
Neither office wants primary administrative responsibility for the fighting pit economy; the jurisdictional ambiguity has never been resolved.
The Ash-and-Iron Decades militarization found Brawlers efficient as reserve depot additions — equipment-independent, immediately deployable, providing close-quarters capability armed units lacked.
Guard Command veterans with Brawler training exist in the current guard corps but are not tracked as a separate category.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Harbor Syndic maintains nominal pit-operator licensing under entertainment venue provisions — in practice a monitoring mechanism rather than control.
The licensed pit circuit coexists with an unlicensed circuit operating in warehouse districts and harbor maintenance facilities outside formal coverage.
Harbor Syndic enforcement corps employ Brawler-tradition practitioners — the techniques suit harbor district enforcement work in cramped, cluttered spaces.
The enforcement corps maintains adversarial working knowledge of active pit circuits: fighters from licensed and unlicensed pits, enforcement corps members, and informal debt enforcers often come from the same training lineages and maintain social relationships crossing institutional boundaries.
The Brawler tradition is most deeply institutionally embedded in Kowloon of all five cities, through both the fighting pit economy and the enforcement functions that depend on the same skill base.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's frontier context gives Brawler practitioners specific operational utility that Wall Command acknowledges without formalizing: close-quarters ability functioning without weapon maintenance or resupply, valuable in extended patrol or siege conditions.
Wall Command's informal assessment rates the tradition highly for interior defense positions and prisoner handling, where lethal weapon use creates its own problems.
Kiess's generally non-restrictive attitude toward physical practice traditions means Brawlers face fewer registry complications here than in Midgaard.
Frontier communities adjacent to Kiess have a higher proportion of Brawler-trained defenders than comparable communities adjacent to other cities, reflecting both practical utility and low institutional barrier.

