Rakuen's Ember Warden doctrine explicitly values Brawler capability for communal defense roles. Resource constraints make equipment-independent fighters more cost-effective than weapon-dependent ones.
The Canopy Compact's collective accountability model fits the Brawler tradition's practical orientation — demonstration-based instruction works within community training frameworks without creating jurisdictional tensions.
Rakuen maintains informal fighting pit equivalents — practice grounds where Brawler skill is tested against resistance — as part of training infrastructure, keeping the quality-verification mechanism functional without the harbor district context.

